<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. botosaneanui" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="botosaneanui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. botosaneanui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. chiriquiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="chiriquiensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. chiriquiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. viridis" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="viridis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. viridis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on characteristics of the phallus, as discussed under 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. botosaneanui" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" rank="species" species="botosaneanui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">L. botosaneanui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson &amp; Holzenthal" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Leucotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leucotrichia hispida" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hispida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Leucotrichia hispida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized using the tuft of setae on the posteroventral projection of sternum VIII and the lack of any external spines or sclerites on the apex of phallus.
</paragraph>
